Let $f(x) = a_nx^n + a_{n-1}x^{n-1} + \cdots + a_2x^2 + a_1x + a_0$, where $a_n \neq 0$. Then,
\begin{align*}
f(1) &= a_n + a_{n-1} + \cdots + a_2 + a_1 + a_0 = 2, \\
f(2) &= 2^n a_n + 2^{n-1}a_{n-1} + \cdots + 2^2a_2 + 2a_1 + a_0 = 3.
\end{align*}
We want to find the remainder when $f(x)$ is divided by $(x-1)(x-2)$. This remainder will have degree at most 1, so we can write it in the form $ax + b$. Then,
\begin{align*}
f(x) &= (x-1)(x-2)q(x) + ax + b,
\end{align*}
where $q(x)$ is the quotient when $f(x)$ is divided by $(x-1)(x-2)$. Substituting $x=1$ and $x=2$ into this equation, we get
\begin{align*}
2 &= f(1) = (1-1)(1-2)q(1) + a(1) + b = a + b, \\
3 &= f(2) = (2-1)(2-2)q(2) + a(2) + b = 2a + b.
\end{align*}
Solving this system of equations, we find that $a = 2$ and $b = 1$. Therefore, the remainder when $f(x)$ is divided by $(x-1)(x-2)$ is $\boxed{2x + 1}$.</thinking> <answer>2x + 1</answer>

